description.plain:
Claire Elizabeth Cottrill (born August 18, 1998), better known by her stage name Clairo, is an American singer-songwriter from Atlanta, Georgia.

She was born in Atlanta, GA, where she lived for seven years, and then she moved to Bellevue, WA and eventually Carlisle, MA.

Her parents are marketing executive Geoff Cottrill and photographer Allie E. Cottrill, who influenced her music taste. Clairo told Beats 1, “My dad is the reason why I love Al Green so much, and my mom is the reason why I love Cocteau Twins so much.”

Clairo’s first EP, titled Do U Wanna Fall In Love?, was released in December of 2014.

She originally rose to prominence with her song “Pretty Girl”, which was released in 2017 and soon went viral. Her first full-length, Immunity, was released in 2019.

Clairo’s second studio album Sling was released July 16, 2021.

description.plain:
“Sofia” is third single from Clairo’s debut album, Immunity. “Sofia” is about Clairo’s first crushes on women such as director Sofia Coppola or actress Sofia Vergara. In this song she talks about a period of time where she was discovering her sexuality. Clairo describes “Sofia” as an “empowering” track in an interview with Coup de Main, stating:

It was important to me that “Sofia” was celebratory because it should be celebrated. At the end of the day it’s something that I’m really proud of and I’m really happy that I can look at the world that way – that I can find beauty in women.

description.plain:
“Pretty Girl” is about a relationship Clairo had where she felt she needed to be the perfect girl for another person. Whether that was wearing makeup, doing her hair, wearing things they liked, or even changing the way she spoke. Eventually, things were broken off, and she’s better off. According to Pitchfork, “Pretty Girl” is a song about changing for a relationship and losing yourself along the way.

The song was originally recorded on GarageBand for a cassette compilation that was limited to 250 copies.

songs.full_title: Bags by Clairo
songs.title: Bags

description.plain:
“Bags” is the first single from Clairo’s debut album Immunity. It was first teased on May 24, 2019, with Clairo announcing that the track would be available at midnight.

Co-produced by Rostam, the song sheds the hazy, lo-fi, aesthetic prevalent in Clairo’s previous work. Instead, the track is brighter and more focused, embracing soft guitar, wavy synths, and twinkling piano, bringing a new sheen to Clairo’s music. “Bags” was inspired by Clairo’s first time with a girl,  lyrically presenting a narrative where she struggles to tell her love interest that she’s crushing on them, hard.

In October 2019, Pitchfork ranked the song at #123 in their “The 200 Best Songs of the 2010s” list.

description.plain:
“Flaming Hot Cheetos” is the second track and first single from Clairo’s EP, diary 001. It acquired its name simply because Clairo was eating them when making the demo.

It’s a song about one of her past relationships, Clairo stated:

The song was sort of a struggle between one side of me trying to ‘snap out of it’, and the other side of me still wishing that things were how they used to be.

The song was produced and written by Clairo herself and it was released in June 2017.

songs.title: Amoeba

description.plain:
“Amoeba” is perhaps the most groovy track from Clairo’s sophomore album Sling. Amoebas are unicellular organisms, and the noun comes from the greek amoibe which means “change, alteration, exchange”. As stated by the singer, the theme of the song is in fact changing her priorities:

 It’s about prioritizing the wrong things. I’d go out on tour and forget to call my family and my friends, forget to eat, then come home and realize my hair’s falling out because I’m not taking care of myself.

On August 6, 2021, Rolling Stone posted a video of Clairo and producer Jack Antonoff breaking down the track, explaining some of the lyrics and production.

songs.title: 4EVER

description.plain:
With its “bedroom pop” vibes and a coming-of-age lyrical style, “4EVER” is the fourth track and third single off of Clairo’s 2018 debut EP, diary 001.

Clairo herself dove into the song for Genius' video series, Verified. She mentioned how the song was born from a period of pre-college anxiety, noting the fact that she wasn’t sure if she would find better friends than those she already had at school:

I’ve made the best friends I’ve ever had at school. They are the first people I’ve met that have really wanted me to grow and want me to be different and are okay with me being weird and trying out new ideas.

songs.title: Hello?

description.plain:
“Hello” is the first collaboration between American singer-songwriter Clairo and Irish rapper Rejjie Snow. Clairo sings about a passionate romance strained by physical and emotional separation, while Rejjie reminisces on the relationship’s origins.

The self-produced instrumental features a simple two-chord synth loop and a bouncy drum beat, evocative of Clairo’s previous instrumental for her SoundCloud hit “Flaming Hot Cheetos.”

songs.full_title: Alewife by Clairo
songs.title: Alewife

description.plain:
On “Alewife,” Clairo expresses her gratitude to her friend Alexa, who helped stop her from ending her life when she was in the eighth grade. Intially dubbed, “Eighth Grade,” the song is named after a train station in Massachusetts, near the town where Clairo spent most of her childhood.

Clairo gracefully recalls details from the sad event in an emotional yet mild-mannered fashion over an ethereal track. The track is based around an acoustic guitar, featuring glimmering piano, reverent drums, and dampened overdriven bass. Originally, Clairo opted for an electric guitar in “Alewife”, but was asked to re-record the parts by co-producer Rostam.

In October 2019, a podcast episode with Clairo and Rostam was posted by Song Exploder, in which the duo talked about the production of the track, from its beginning in Truth Studios, LA to the final product. Alexa also appears in the episode, briefly touching on her reaction to hearing “Alewife.”

description.plain:
After coming out in March 2018, Clairo began releasing more songs that openly used female pronouns. Leading into the more overt track “Sofia,” “Softly” sees Clairo confessing her love for another girl, a feeling she battled with as a teenager.

She told them in May 2019:

I’ve been struggling with this my whole life. I know I love people and I’m acknowledging that as something that’s happening to me.

songs.full_title: I Wouldn't Ask You by Clairo
songs.title: I Wouldn’t Ask You

description.plain:
On “I Wouldn’t Ask You”, Clairo sings about a time in her life when she was hospitalized from severe juvenile rheumatoid arthritis and cared for by her boyfriend at the time, as she divulged in a July 2019 interview with PAPER. Throughout the song, Clairo expresses gratitude to her lover for being her caretaker, while also conveying varying degrees of intimacy.

The song has two distinct conceptual parts, marked by a distinguishable change in instrumentation, tone, and style. The first part has a slow tempo, backed by a subtle piano accompaniment, similar to the opening track “Alewife.” During this part, Clairo sings with a warbly vocoded voice, as she describes her condition in the hospital, hinting at feelings of helplessness and isolation from her partner. The song then morphs into a more upbeat R&B groove, in which Clairo suddenly sings from a position of full intimacy to her partner, free from the limitations of her arthritis.

songs.title: Sinking

description.plain:
Throughout “Sinking”, Clairo alludes to her juvenile rheumatoid arthritis, a condition she has had since the age of 17. Although “Sinking” isn’t the only track from Immunity to discuss her arthritis, with final song “I Wouldn’t Ask You” addressing her struggle when she was first diagnosed.

“Sinking”  was written during a period when Clairo had particularly bad flares, so bad she struggled to even make it to the studio. She commented on the song’s lyrics to Pitchfork:

If you really pay attention to what’s going on, you can tell that it’s about someone dealing with pain. That’s how arthritis works: You don’t understand it until you look closely enough.

songs.title: Just For Today

description.plain:
Inspired by her experiences with anxiety and depression, Clairo penned “Just For Today,” referencing the night she joined the National Suicide Prevention Lifeline’s chat room. This isn’t the first time Clairo has sung candidly about her mental health, discussing suicide in her August 2019 track “Alewife.”

On January 25, 2021, Clairo shared an acoustic snippet of the track to Instagram, telling fans she had written it the night before. In her July 2021 interview for Rolling Stone, Clairo revealed that “Just For Today” wasn’t initially on her album Sling, but was added after she read the feedback from fans:

It was a kind of response I had never really seen.

As the partridge sitteth on eggs, and hatcheth them not; so he that getteth riches, and not by right, shall leave them in the midst of his days, and at his end shall be a fool.

The partridge most likely refers to her partner, who only benefits from Clairo’s love and affection, without giving anything in return.

songs.full_title: Zinnias by Clairo
songs.title: Zinnias

description.plain:
Zinnias is a much more apprehensive song on Sling, where Clairo can be heard expressing her thoughts on her becoming a mother, and how it’d affect the people around her, while also reflecting on her relations with others.

A Zinnias is a species of flower which is notable for blooming in the hottest times of the year, with the prime example of June. This flower, alongside the southern Cosmos, are the two flowers mentioned on this record. Clairo appears to be envisioning herself as the Zinnias plant, while her brother is the southern Cosmos.

This tracks themes of motherhood can be seen in lines primarily found in the chorus, where she also mentions her sister. A scene can be visualized where she lives a life where she settles down and has a child, a life where she doesn’t write music, but rather settles down. In an interview with Rolling Stone, Clairo alludes to this, where she mentions how she would’ve quit music without Sling

This record has changed everything for me, because I was fully going to quit music.

The tracks themes of distancing can be found in verse 1, where Clairo speaks of days where she felt close to her brother, compared to the present day, where she struggles to even find conversation with him. She recalls missing those old times and feeling saddened by her current situation.

songs.full_title: ​lying has to stop by Clairo
songs.title: ​lying has to stop

description.plain:
This unreleased SoundCloud track by Clairo (aka Claire Cottrill), is a cover of Soft Hair’s 2016 hit “Lying Has To Stop”, stylized here as “lying has to stop”.

Albeit a cover, Clairo’s rendition of the song is musically vastly different from the original and has a distinctly unique feel to it. While the original features a steady high-tempo drum beat and a bouncy & melodic keyboard melody that gives the song a slightly electronic quality, Clairo’s version is slow-moving in every way, somber, and airy, to the point of almost being sedating.

The song also features a drum-kit produced beat throughout, but the instrumentals and Clairo’s vocals are what really gives the song its celestial anesthetic feel. The backing instrumentals are made up of a beautiful sustained synthesizer notes, mimicking an orchestral strings section, as well as a chime-like xylophone riff at various points in the song. Most notably, Clairo’s vocals are unforgettable, as she summons up all the sorrow she can muster and delivers the mournful lyrics in a way that sounds angelic.

Anytime Clairo covers a song she makes it her own and it is always something to behold. In the case of “lying has to stop” she has fundamentally changed its sound, transforming an experimental pop song into a mournful dream pop ballad.
